    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Cincinnati June 19&#47;78<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear &#38; kind teacher<lb/></p>
            <p>Your postal just received &#38; was glad<lb/> to learn form it&#44; that you and all your<lb/> family are doing well.  Although I have<lb/> very much work on hand to accomplish<lb/> before the coming week&#44; yet&#44; I never think<lb/> my time so well employed&#44; as when I think<lb/> if employed <del>for</del> by writing to you.  You<lb/> have given me a great share of your<lb/> time while being at your city&#59; you shall<lb/> now have mine&#44; and the greatest part of<lb/> it.<lb/></p>
            <p>Am now at work to write my speech<lb/> for the final entertainment of the H. U. C.&#44;<lb/> which will take place on Sunday the 30th<lb/> inst..  I can give you here merely the outline<lb/> of the subject which I am writing about&#59; but<lb/> as to the merit of the composition &#38; the manner<lb/> in which I will deliver it&#44; you will judge when you<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p><sic>when you</sic> come to this city and hear it<lb/> spoken.  The scene <del>opened</del> represented will be a club<lb/> house&#44; where two young men are found to<lb/> be engaged in a very interesting argument&#44;<lb/> the one tries to convince the other that<lb/> the ancient mode of living is preferable<lb/> to the modern one&#59; while the other insists<lb/> upon and proves by historical facts<lb/> that the modern style of living is&#44; by far<lb/> superior to the ancient.  While they are thus<lb/> arguing warmly&#44; then I enter &#38; stand<lb/> aside to listen to their arguments.  As<lb/> soon as they perceive that I am in the<lb/> room they call me up and request<lb/> me to decide the question<del>s</del> which being<lb/> prepared before hand for that in<lb/>vitation I try to refute the points given<lb/> by both parties.  The entire dialogue<lb/> will be original speeches&#59; and we did<lb/> that on account to try ourselves&#44;<lb/> whether we are able to accomplish<lb/> such an undertaking&#44; <del>alth</del> though<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>very serious in its nature <sic>skilful</sic><lb/> judges will undoubtedly state their im&#45;<lb/>partial criticism and will discern<lb/> and acknowledge its merit&#59; the ignorant<lb/> will&#44; without knowing why&#44; submit to<lb/> the opinion expressed by the learned one.<lb/></p>
            <p>I had no <hi rend="underline">chance</hi> opportunity to<lb/> see Mr. Ezekiel&#44; but I will see him<lb/> this afternoon.  Write me please once<lb/> more before you leave for this city &#38;<lb/> state on which train you will arrive&#44;<lb/> so that I may know positively where<lb/> &#38; when to meet you.<lb/></p>
            <p>My love to all<lb/>
            Yours&#44; as ever<lb/>
            I Rubenstein<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
